    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-02-17T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-02-17T06:00:00-05:00" n="815"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d815">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/823: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-02-17T20:00:00+09:00"
                            >February 17, 1939—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 18—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Department’s 17, January 19, 9 p.m., Canton Maritime Customs. The procedure
                    envisaged in Department’s paragraph numbered 1 was followed in an interview with
                    the Minister for Foreign Affairs today. The Minister replied that he took note
                    of my statement but made no further comment.<note n="56" xml:id="d815fn56">See
                        Ambassador Grew’s memorandum of February 17, <ref
                            target="frus1931-41v01#pg_747">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 747</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
